name: Just as I Am
comments: The lyrics by Charlotte Elliott were first published in 1836. The music was originally written by William Bradbury in 1849. Bradbury adapted Elliott's text to fit his tune. First two verses - Just as I am, without one plea, But that Thy blood was shed for me, And that Thou bid’st me come to Thee, O Lamb of God, I come! I come! Just as I am, and waiting not To rid my soul of one dark blot; To Thee whose blood can cleanse each spot, O Lamb of God, I come, I come!

name: Just Because
comments: "Just Because" was copyrighted by the Shelton Brothers and Sid Robin in the mid 1930s, when the Shelton Brothers first recorded this song under their own name. The same song, however, was recorded by Nelstone's Hawaiians in the late 1920s and by the Lone Star Cowboys in 1933. In 1948 the Peer International Corporation sued Leeds Music and Columbia records alleging infringement on the Shelton/Shelton/Robin composition, but with the defendants arguing “that the music had been in the public domain prior to Touchstone’s and Nelson’s writing, and that the latter had copied and appropriated substantial portions of their version from prior copyrights.” It's unclear in favour of whom the court eventually ruled.

name: It Can't Be Wrong
comments: The melody for this work was written by Max Steiner as a theme used in the background music for the Warner Brothers' film, "Now Voyager." In late 1942, after the film was completed, Kim Gannon wrote the lyrics and the song was published. However, the American Federation of Musicians were on strike and, consequently, no recordings were made at that time. Nevertheless, the song was heavily plugged by the publisher and by early 1943 it was one of the top songs in sheet music sales and radio play. The first recording was released on Hit, a label noted for producing records in Mexico to avoid the strike restrictions.

name: An die Freude [poem]
comments: In English: "To Joy". An ode celebrating the brotherhood and unity of all mankind, first published in Schiller's 1786 review "Thalia". Schiller later made some revisions to the poem, which was re-published posthumously in 1808 including the famous line "Alle Menschen werden Brüder".  It is this re-published version that Beethoven set to music.

name: Sinfonie Nr. 9 in D-Moll, IV. Satz
comments: Translates to "Symphony No. 9 in D Minor, 4th Movement". It is the last and longest part of Beethoven's Ninth Symphony, which is also known as Sinfonie mit Schluss-Chor über Schillers Ode "An die Freude" (translating to Symphony with a Final Chorus on Schiller's Ode "To Joy". Composed 1818 to 1824, the symphony was first performed on May 7, 1824 in the Kärntnertortheater in Vienna, Austria.
adapted_from: An die Freude [poem] written by Friedrich Schiller
